@node mu4e link opening
@section mu4e link opening

@findex ace-link-extras-mu4e
When reading email in @samp{mu4e-view-mode}, the standard @code{ace-link-mu4e} command works well for most HTML renderers. However, if @code{mm-text-html-renderer} is set to @code{w3m}, the link collection mechanism differs: links are stored as @samp{w3m} text properties rather than @samp{shr} overlays.

The command @code{ace-link-extras-mu4e} detects which renderer is active and adapts accordingly. When @samp{w3m} is the renderer, it collects links using @code{ace-link--w3m-collect}, lets you select one via @samp{avy}, and then opens the selected URL with @code{browse-url}. This means the link is opened according to your @code{browse-url-handlers} configuration (which may route it to @samp{eww}, Chrome, Firefox, or another browser) rather than being opened inside @samp{w3m} itself.

When any other renderer is active, the command falls back to the standard @code{ace-link-mu4e} behavior.

@node EWW link actions
@section EWW link actions

@findex ace-link-extras-eww-externally
@findex ace-link-extras-eww-new-buffer
The standard @code{ace-link-eww} command opens the selected link in the current @samp{eww} buffer. Two additional commands provide alternative targets:

@itemize
@item
@code{ace-link-extras-eww-externally} opens the selected link using the browser specified by @code{browse-url-secondary-browser-function}. Internally, it passes a prefix argument of @samp{(4)} to @code{ace-link-eww}. Use this when you want to view a page in a full graphical browser without leaving your @samp{eww} session.

@item
@code{ace-link-extras-eww-new-buffer} opens the selected link in a new @samp{eww} buffer, preserving the current page. Internally, it passes a prefix argument of @samp{(16)} to @code{ace-link-eww}. This is useful when you want to keep multiple pages open for comparison.
@end itemize

@node Org-roam link following
@section Org-roam link following

@findex ace-link-extras-org-roam
The @samp{org-roam} backlink sidebar (@samp{org-roam-mode} buffers) displays Org links that are not in a standard Org buffer, so @code{ace-link-org} alone does not handle the navigation correctly. The command @code{ace-link-extras-org-roam} uses @code{ace-link--org-collect} to gather link positions and @samp{avy} to let you select one, then calls @code{org-roam-preview-visit} to navigate to the linked node.

